definition.value: An SCF ubiquitin ligase complex in which the F-box protein is YLR224W in S. cerevisiae.
An SCF ubiquitin ligase complex in which the F-box protein is YLR352W in S. cerevisiae.
An SCF ubiquitin ligase complex in which the F-box protein is Hrt3 in S. cerevisiae (Pof7 in S. pombe).

Interacting selectively and non-covalently with any member of the signal transducers and activators of transcription (STAT) protein family. STATs are, as the name indicates, both signal transducers and transcription factors. STATs are activated by cytokines and some growth factors and thus control important biological processes including cell growth, cell differentiation, apoptosis and immune responses.

Interacting selectively and non-covalently with any member of the suppressor of cytokine signaling (SOCS) family of proteins. SOCS represent an important mechanism to extinguish cytokine and growth factor receptor signaling. Individual SOCS proteins are typically induced by specific cytokines and growth factors, thereby generating a negative feedback loop. SOCS proteins have important functions in development and homeostasis, and in disease, particularly tumor suppression and anti-inflammatory functions.
The cytoplasm of a secondary organism with which the first organism is interacting.
Catalysis of the transmembrane transfer of cations by a channel that opens when phosphatidylinositol-3,5-bisphosphate has been bound by the channel complex or one of its constituent parts.
The anterior most point of a dinoflagellate epicone.
The anterior most point of a dinoflagellate hypocone.
A cell surface furrow (or groove) found on a dinoflagellate apex. It typically loops around the apex.
A horn-shaped dinoflagellate apex found in thecate species.
A horn-shaped dinoflagellate antapex found in thecate species.
The part of the viral terminase complex that contains the translocase activity. The large subunit typically comprises a pentameric protein complex.
Part of the virion that may be used to recognize, attach and inject the viral genome and accessory proteins into the host cell.

The part of the viral capsid that comprises the most common capsomere type. For example, in a T-eq-3 icosahedral capsid, which is composed of 12 pentameric and 20 hexameric capsomeres, the hexameric capsomeres are major subunits.

The part of the viral capsid that comprises the less common capsomere type. For example, in a T-eq-3 icosahedral capsid, which is composed of 12 pentameric and 20 hexameric capsomeres, the pentameric capsomeres are minor subunits.
The part of the viral tail that comprises the most common subunit type.
The part of the viral tail that comprises the least common subunit type.
Component of the virus capsid (head), located on the outer head surface. Involved in the stabilization of the head structure and usually non-essential.
A type of capsid decoration composed of fiber structures.
The basal end of the virus tail, which is used by the virus to attach to the host cell.
The fibrous region of the virus tail used to scan, recognize and attach to the host cell.
Multiprotein component at the distal (head) end of the virus tail to which fibers of tailed viruses may be attached.
The internal tube of the contractile tails of some viruses. The virus tail tube is the channel for DNA ejection into the host cytoplasm.
The external contractile envelope of the tail of some viruses. Its contraction ensures ejection of the virus DNA into the host cytoplasm.
The tube of the non-contractile tails of some viruses.
A short structure attached to an icosahedral virion capsid, and used for attachment to the host cell.
A region of constriction located below the head and above the tail sheath of viruses with contractile tails (Myoviridae).
A small disk located at the base of some icosahedral virus capsids.
A fiber attached to the collar structure of some icosahedral viral capsids.
A fiber attached to the neck at the base of some icosahedral viral capsids.

label.value: type V protein secretion system complex

definition.value: A complex of proteins that permits the translocation of proteins across the outer membrane via a transmembrane pore, formed by a beta-barrel, into the extracellular milieu or directly into host cells -  the secreted proteins contain all the information required for translocation of an effector molecule through the cell envelope. The type V secretion systems includes the autotransporters (type Va), the two-partner secretion system (type Vb) and the Oca family (type Vc).
The region of a virus contained within the capsid shell, and usually containing the viral genome and accessory proteins.
Interacting selectively and non-covalently with G-rich, single-stranded, telomere-associated DNA.
Catalysis of the reaction -  phosphopolynucleotide + H2O -eq- polynucleotide + phosphate.

label.value: nucleotide phosphatase activity, acting on free nucleotides

definition.value: Catalysis of the reaction -  nucleotide + H2O -eq- nucleotide + phosphate.

The junction between the axon of a motor neuron and a muscle fiber. In response to the arrival of action potentials, the presynaptic button releases molecules of neurotransmitters into the synaptic cleft. These diffuse across the cleft and transmit the signal to the postsynaptic membrane of the muscle fiber, leading to a post-synaptic potential responsible for muscle contraction.

The junction between the axon of a motor neuron and a muscle fiber. In response to the arrival of action potentials, the presynaptic button releases molecules of neurotransmitters into the synaptic cleft. These diffuse across the cleft and transmit the signal to the postsynaptic membrane of the muscle fiber, leading to a change in post-synaptic potential that inhibits muscle contraction.

label.value: neuromuscular junction of skeletal muscle fiber

definition.value: A neuromuscular junction in which the target muscle cell is a skeletal muscle fiber.
A neuromuscular junction in which the target muscle cell is a myotube.

label.value: neuromuscular junction of somatic muscle myotube

definition.value: A neuromuscular junction in which the target muscle cell is a somatic muscle myotube, such as an arthropod somatic muscle cell.

label.value: excitatory neuromuscular junction of somatic myotube

definition.value: A neuromuscular junction that functions in the excitation of somatic muscle myotubes, such as an arthropod somatic muscle cells.

label.value: inhibitory neuromuscular junction of somatic myotube

definition.value: A neuromuscular junction that functions in the inhibition of somatic muscle myotube contraction. Examples of somatic muscle myotubes include the somatic muscle cells of arthropods.
A neuromuscular junction in which the target muscle cell is a somatic muscle cell, such as those found in nematodes and arthropods.

label.value: direct ligand regulated sequence-specific DNA binding transcription factor activity

definition.value: A DNA binding transcription factor activity that is directly regulated by binding of a ligand to the protein with this activity.  Examples include the lac and trp repressors in E.coli and many steroid hormone receptors.
A transmembrane protein complex that functions in ATPase dependent active transport across a membrane.
A spherical, electron dense, cytoplasmic structure that is involved in de novo assembly of centrioles.
Nucleus with two or more lobes connected by a thin filament that contains no internal chromatin.  Examples include the nuclei of mature basophils, eosinophils and neutrophils in mice and humans.

label.value: lumenal side of transport vesicle membrane

definition.value: The side (leaflet) of the transport vesicle membrane that faces the lumen.

label.value: cytoplasmic side of transport vesicle membrane

definition.value: The side (leaflet) of the transport vesicle membrane that faces the cytoplasm.
